orrectOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing oculogyric crisis, an acute dystonic reaction likely precipitated by the administration of an antipsychotic. Acute dystonias are more likely to occur with first-generation antipsychotics. Treatment is with the anticholinergic agent \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenzatropine\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther extrapyramidal side effects of antipsychotics include parkinsonism, tardive dyskinesia and akathisia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropanolol\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ediazepam\u003C/strong\u003E are treatments for akathisia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBromocriptine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecyproheptadine\u003C/strong\u003E are used for neuroleptic malignant syndrome and serotonin syndrome, respectively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute dystonias are a recognised side effect of first-generation antipsychotics."],"references":["Schizophrenia and related psychoses [Internet]. eTG Complete. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Antipsychotic adverse effects [internet]. eTG complete. 2021. Available from https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Psychotropic\u0026topicfile=antipsychotic-adverse-effects\u0026guidelinename=Psychotropic\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e2455#toc_d1e2455 [Accessed April 2023]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2407"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T15:28:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T15:28:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2407"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106664"}}},"meta":{